{
  "The formula for calculating the natural rate of increase (NIR) is:": "",
  "Birth rate multiplied by death rate": "",
  "Total population divided by land area": "",
  "Crude birth rate minus crude death rate": "",
  "Death rate minus birth rate": "",
  "The natural rate of increase equals the crude birth rate minus the crude death rate. When expressed per 1,000 people, it shows the annual natural population change excluding migration. A positive NIR indicates growth, while a negative NIR indicates decline.": "",
  "A country has a CBR of 25 per 1,000 and a CDR of 10 per 1,000. What is the natural rate of increase as a percentage?": "",
  "3.5%": "",
  "0.5%": "",
  "1.5%": "",
  "2.5%": "",
  "NIR = (CBR - CDR) / 10 = (25 - 10) / 10 = 1.5%. The division by 10 converts from per 1,000 to a percentage. This means the population is growing at 1.5% per year from natural increase alone, which would produce a doubling time of about 47 years.": "",
  "Using the Rule of 70, a population growing at 3.5% per year will double in approximately:": "",
  "10 years": "",
  "35 years": "",
  "20 years": "",
  "70 years": "",
  "Doubling time = 70 / growth rate percentage = 70 / 3.5 = 20 years. This rapid doubling time is characteristic of the fastest-growing countries in the world, where populations can double within a single generation.": "",
  "If a population of 5 million has a CBR of 30 per 1,000 and a CDR of 12 per 1,000, how many people are added to the population per year (ignoring migration)?": "",
  "45,000": "",
  "90,000": "",
  "150,000": "",
  "60,000": "",
  "Annual natural increase = Population x (CBR - CDR) / 1,000 = 5,000,000 x (30 - 12) / 1,000 = 5,000,000 x 18/1,000 = 90,000 people per year. This represents the net natural population increase before accounting for immigration or emigration.": "",
  "The infant mortality rate is calculated as:": "",
  "Total deaths divided by total births": "",
  "Number of infant deaths (under 1 year) per 1,000 live births": "",
  "Deaths during childbirth per 1,000 women": "",
  "Number of deaths of children under 5 per 100,000 population": "",
  "The infant mortality rate (IMR) = (number of deaths of infants under age 1 / number of live births) x 1,000. It is one of the most important demographic indicators, reflecting a country's healthcare quality, nutrition, and socioeconomic development.": "",
  "A population with a growth rate of 1% per year has a doubling time of approximately:": "",
  "50 years": "",
  "100 years": "",
  "Using the Rule of 70: doubling time = 70 / 1 = 70 years. While 1% growth may seem slow, over 70 years the population would double. Over 200 years (about three doubling periods), it would increase eightfold.": "",
  "The total population change equation is:": "",
  "Population change = Deaths - Births + Migration": "",
  "Population change = Births + Deaths": "",
  "Population change = (Births + Immigration) - (Deaths + Emigration)": "",
  "Population change = Birth rate x Death rate": "",
  "The total population change accounts for all four factors: births and immigration add people, while deaths and emigration remove them. This equation captures both natural increase (births minus deaths) and net migration (immigration minus emigration).": "",
  "A country has 800,000 births, 300,000 deaths, 50,000 immigrants, and 20,000 emigrants in one year. The total population change is:": "",
  "1,170,000": "",
  "500,000": "",
  "430,000": "",
  "530,000": "",
  "Population change = (Births + Immigration) - (Deaths + Emigration) = (800,000 + 50,000) - (300,000 + 20,000) = 850,000 - 320,000 = 530,000. The natural increase accounts for 500,000 and net migration adds another 30,000.": "",
  "The dependency ratio is calculated as:": "",
  "Birth rate divided by death rate": "",
  "Working-age population divided by total population": "",
  "Urban population divided by rural population": "",
  "(Population under 15 + population over 64) / population aged 15-64 x 100": "",
  "The dependency ratio measures the number of dependents (under 15 and over 64) per 100 working-age people (15-64). A ratio of 50 means there are 50 dependents per 100 workers. High ratios indicate greater economic burden on the working-age population.": "",
  "If a country has 20 million people under 15, 60 million aged 15-64, and 20 million over 64, what is the dependency ratio?": "",
  "40": "",
  "100": "",
  "150": "",
  "67": "",
  "Dependency ratio = (20M + 20M) / 60M x 100 = 40M / 60M x 100 = 66.7, rounded to 67. This means there are approximately 67 dependents for every 100 working-age people, indicating a moderately high economic burden on the workforce.": "",
  "What is the Rule of 70?": "",
  "A formula that calculates the approximate doubling time of an exponentially growing population by dividing 70 by the growth rate percentage": "",
  "A formula for calculating carrying capacity": "",
  "A rule stating that 70% of all species will go extinct": "",
  "A rule that 70% of population growth occurs in cities": "",
  "The Rule of 70 provides a quick estimate of doubling time: doubling time (years) = 70 / annual growth rate (%). For example, a population growing at 2% doubles in 70/2 = 35 years. The rule works because 70 is an approximation of the natural logarithm of 2 (0.693) multiplied by 100.": "",
  "What is the crude birth rate (CBR)?": "",
  "The number of births per 100 women of childbearing age": "",
  "The total number of children born in a hospital per year": "",
  "The number of live births per 1,000 people in a population in a given year": "",
  "The birth rate adjusted for the age structure of the population": "",
  "The crude birth rate is calculated by dividing the total number of live births in a year by the mid-year population, then multiplying by 1,000. It is termed 'crude' because it does not account for age or sex composition, which can significantly influence birth rates.": "",
  "What is the crude death rate (CDR)?": "",
  "The death rate adjusted for age": "",
  "The number of deaths from infectious diseases per 100,000 people": "",
  "The number of deaths per 1,000 people in a population in a given year": "",
  "The total number of deaths in hospitals per year": "",
  "The crude death rate is calculated by dividing the total number of deaths in a year by the mid-year population, then multiplying by 1,000. Like the CBR, it is 'crude' because it does not adjust for age structure, which heavily influences mortality patterns.": "",
  "What does the term 'per capita' mean in demographic calculations?": "",
  "Per unit of land area": "",
  "Per household, particularly": "",
  "Per person or per individual in the population": "",
  "Per year, particularly regarding": "",
  "Per capita is a Latin term meaning 'per head' or 'per person.' In demographic calculations, per capita rates express a quantity divided by the total population, allowing meaningful comparisons between populations of different sizes.": "",
  "What is net migration rate?": "",
  "The rate at which refugees are accepted into a country": "",
  "The difference between the number of immigrants and emigrants per 1,000 population per year": "",
  "The number of people who leave a country permanently": "",
  "The total number of people who move within a country": "",
  "The net migration rate is the difference between immigration (people entering) and emigration (people leaving) per 1,000 population per year. A positive rate means more people are entering than leaving, while a negative rate indicates net outward migration.": "",
  "What is population density?": "",
  "The total number of people in a country": "",
  "The weight of a population in a given area": "",
  "The number of cities in a country": "",
  "The number of people per unit of area, such as per square kilometer or square mile": "",
  "Population density measures how concentrated a population is within a given area, typically expressed as people per square kilometer or square mile. High-density areas include cities and small countries, while low-density areas include deserts, forests, and sparsely populated countries.": "",
  "What is the growth rate of a population?": "",
  "The percentage change in population size per year, accounting for births, deaths, and migration": "",
  "The total number of births in a year": "",
  "The rate at which cities expand in area": "",
  "The increase in a country's GDP per year": "",
  "The population growth rate is the percentage by which a population increases or decreases per year. It combines natural increase (births minus deaths) and net migration. A growth rate of 2% means the population increases by 2% of its current size each year.": "",
  "What is the age-specific fertility rate?": "",
  "The average age at which women have their first child": "",
  "The crude birth rate divided by the number of age groups": "",
  "The number of live births per 1,000 women of a specific age group in a given year": "",
  "The total number of children born to women of all ages combined": "",
  "The age-specific fertility rate measures births per 1,000 women within a particular age group (e.g., 20-24, 25-29). Summing all age-specific fertility rates gives an estimate of the total fertility rate, providing more detailed information about reproductive patterns than the crude birth rate.": "",
  "What does 'arithmetic growth' mean in population studies?": "",
  "Growth by a constant amount added each time period, producing a straight line on a graph": "",
  "Random fluctuations in population size": "",
  "Growth that doubles every generation": "",
  "Growth by a constant percentage each time period": "",
  "Arithmetic (linear) growth adds the same fixed number of individuals each time period, producing a straight-line graph. Malthus argued that food production grows arithmetically while population grows geometrically (exponentially), meaning population would inevitably outstrip food supply.": "",
  "What is geometric (exponential) growth?": "",
  "Growth that slows as a population approaches carrying capacity": "",
  "Growth where a fixed number of individuals is added each year": "",
  "Growth that alternates between increase and decrease": "",
  "Growth where the population increases by a constant percentage each time period, producing a J-shaped curve": "",
  "Geometric or exponential growth occurs when a population increases by a constant proportion (percentage) each time period. Because the base number grows, each successive increase is larger in absolute terms, producing the characteristic J-shaped curve. This is the growth pattern assumed by the Rule of 70.": "",
  "Country X has a population of 20 million, a CBR of 35 per 1,000, and a CDR of 10 per 1,000. Calculate the natural rate of increase as a percentage and the approximate doubling time.": "",
  "NIR = 3.5%, doubling time = 20 years": "",
  "NIR = 1.5%, doubling time = 47 years": "",
  "NIR = 2.5%, doubling time = 28 years": "",
  "NIR = 4.5%, doubling time = 16 years": "",
  "NIR = (CBR - CDR) / 10 = (35 - 10) / 10 = 2.5%. Doubling time = 70 / 2.5 = 28 years. This means Country X's population will grow from 20 million to 40 million in approximately 28 years if the growth rate remains constant.": "",
  "A city has 500,000 residents, 8,000 births, 4,000 deaths, 3,000 immigrants, and 1,000 emigrants in one year. What is the total population growth rate for that year?": "",
  "2.0%": "",
  "0.8%": "",
  "1.6%": "",
  "1.2%": "",
  "Total change = (8,000 + 3,000) - (4,000 + 1,000) = 11,000 - 5,000 = 6,000 people. Growth rate = (6,000 / 500,000) x 100 = 1.2%. This rate includes both natural increase (0.8%) and net migration (0.4%).": "",
  "Country A has a population of 10 million and grows at 2% per year. Country B has a population of 40 million and grows at 0.5% per year. In how many years will Country A's population equal Country B's current population?": "",
  "35 years (one doubling from 10M to 20M, then another to 40M = two doublings at 35 years each = 70 years)": "",
  "140 years": "",
  "70 years (two doublings: 10M to 20M in 35 years, 20M to 40M in another 35 years)": "",
  "It will never reach 40 million": "",
  "Country A needs to quadruple (10M to 40M), which requires two doubling periods. At 2% growth, doubling time = 70/2 = 35 years. Two doublings = 70 years. Note that Country B will also have grown during this time, so Country A would still be smaller than Country B's future population.": "",
  "An AP student is given this data: Country with 50 million people, CBR = 22, CDR = 8, immigration rate = 3 per 1,000, emigration rate = 1 per 1,000. Calculate the total annual population growth rate and the total number of people added per year.": "",
  "Growth rate = 2.2%, people added = 1,100,000": "",
  "Growth rate = 1.6%, people added = 800,000": "",
  "Growth rate = 1.4%, people added = 700,000": "",
  "Growth rate = 1.0%, people added = 500,000": "",
  "Natural increase rate = (22 - 8) / 10 = 1.4%. Net migration rate = (3 - 1) / 10 = 0.2%. Total growth rate = 1.4% + 0.2% = 1.6%. People added = 50,000,000 x 0.016 = 800,000 per year.": "",
  "Two countries start with 100 million people each in 2020. Country A grows at 0.5% per year and Country B at 2.5% per year. An AP question asks approximately how many people Country B will have added by 2048 compared to Country A. What is the answer?": "",
  "Both countries add the same number of people": "",
  "Country B adds about 15 million more than Country A": "",
  "Country B adds about 85 million more than Country A": "",
  "Country A adds more people than Country B": "",
  "In 28 years: Country A at 0.5% doubles in 140 years, so grows about 15% to ~115 million (added ~15M). Country B at 2.5% doubles in 28 years to 200 million (added ~100M). Country B adds about 85 million more than Country A, demonstrating how small differences in growth rates compound dramatically.": "",
  "A developing nation reports the following data: 45,000 live births, 200 infant deaths, total population of 2 million, and 12,000 total deaths. Calculate the IMR and the CBR.": "",
  "IMR = 200 per 1,000; CBR = 45 per 1,000": "",
  "IMR = 4.4 per 1,000; CBR = 22.5 per 1,000": "",
  "IMR = 10 per 1,000; CBR = 30 per 1,000": "",
  "IMR = 44 per 1,000; CBR = 6 per 1,000": "",
  "IMR = (infant deaths / live births) x 1,000 = (200 / 45,000) x 1,000 = 4.4 per 1,000 live births. CBR = (total births / total population) x 1,000 = (45,000 / 2,000,000) x 1,000 = 22.5 per 1,000. The low IMR suggests good infant healthcare despite moderate birth rates.": "",
  "A country has 30 million people under 15, 50 million aged 15-64, and 20 million over 64. Calculate the total dependency ratio and identify whether the youth or elderly dependency is greater.": "",
  "Total dependency ratio = 60; elderly dependency is greater": "",
  "Total dependency ratio = 50; elderly dependency is greater": "",
  "Total dependency ratio = 100; youth dependency is greater": "",
  "Total dependency ratio = 75; they are equal": "",
  "Total dependency ratio = (30M + 20M) / 50M x 100 = 100. This means there are 100 dependents per 100 workers. Youth dependency = 30/50 x 100 = 60, elderly dependency = 20/50 x 100 = 40. Youth dependency (60) is greater than elderly dependency (40).": "",
  "The world population was approximately 6 billion in 1999 and 8 billion in 2022. An AP exam asks you to calculate the average annual growth rate during this 23-year period. Which is closest?": "",
  "3.3% per year": "",
  "1.25% per year": "",
  "2.0% per year": "",
  "0.5% per year": "",
  "The population grew by 2 billion out of 6 billion, or 33.3%, over 23 years. Average annual rate = approximately 33.3% / 23 = 1.45%, but using compound growth, the rate is closer to 1.25% per year. Using the Rule of 70, a 1.25% rate gives a doubling time of 56 years, consistent with the roughly one-third increase over 23 years.": "",
  "An AP problem provides: Country with CBR = 18, CDR = 9, TFR = 2.0, IMR = 5, life expectancy = 78 years. You are asked to classify this country by DTM stage and predict future population trends. What is the correct classification?": "",
  "Stage 1; high birth and death rates": "",
  "Stage 4; low growth with potential transition to Stage 5 decline as TFR is near but slightly below replacement": "",
  "Stage 2; rapid population growth expected": "",
  "Stage 3; birth rates declining rapidly": "",
  "Low CBR (18), low CDR (9), near-replacement TFR (2.0), very low IMR (5), and high life expectancy (78) are all hallmarks of a Stage 4 country. With TFR at 2.0, slightly below the 2.1 replacement level, the population may begin to slowly decline without immigration, suggesting a possible transition to Stage 5.": "",
  "An AP free-response question asks you to use the I=PAT equation to compare the environmental impact of Country A (population 300 million, GDP per capita $50,000, energy intensity 0.5 kg CO2 per dollar GDP) versus Country B (population 1 billion, GDP per capita $3,000, energy intensity 1.0 kg CO2 per dollar GDP). Which country has a greater total carbon footprint?": "",
  "Country B, because it has higher energy intensity": "",
  "Both countries have identical carbon footprints": "",
  "Country B, because it has a larger population": "",
  "Country A, because 300M x $50,000 x 0.5 = 7.5 trillion kg CO2 exceeds Country B's 1B x $3,000 x 1.0 = 3 trillion kg CO2": "",
  "Using I = P x A x T: Country A = 300,000,000 x 50,000 x 0.5 = 7.5 trillion kg CO2. Country B = 1,000,000,000 x 3,000 x 1.0 = 3 trillion kg CO2. Despite having one-third the population, Country A's much higher affluence produces 2.5 times the total carbon impact, illustrating why consumption patterns matter as much as population size.": ""
}